Date:9/21/2012 11:01:35 AM
From:NikhilJog
Sergio - Thanks. My method is very simple - it involves looking at hard and
soft catalysts in addition to fundamentals.

I try to understand the business really well, its drivers and understand the
catalysts before "Really" looking at fundamentals. Then i marry fundamentals
with the catalysts and i know how the stock is going to move, timeline, so on
and so forth. I DO NOT read sell side reports or listen to mgt, unless I have
first done my own homework.

So this is super simple answer to your question. Ofcourse, there is tonnes of
analysis that goes into it.

For example - i look at 25 quarters of data and go back atleast 6 years when i
look at numbers for a firm. When i do that, " I personally download ALL MY DATA
from SEC filings and not depend on any website or even Bloomberg". Or when i
look at EPS, i will usually model normalized earnings as opposed to just
looking at EPS. If I am looking at a spin-off, i will look at upside created by
the spin for the holdco, example being Marriott where i modeled a t $8-$10
upside from the spin. When i wrote it, MAR was at 32 and today its touching
$41/$42. Or sometimes i will play spin's as long/short. Look at my RAH/POST
analysis. I put one for my clients on CVC last yr which is not on seeking alpha
( shorting CVC and going long AMCX). You guys don;t see all my ideas. Sometimes
I will look at upcoming contracts and JV's in addition to fundamentals. ACIW
and TYL are such example that i wrote about when they were trading at 30 and 20
respectively OR WXS when I wrote in mid 2010 when it was trading around $31.

I can go on and on, but you get the idea. So it boils to few basic things -
"really understanding the company, marrying my catalysts with good
fundamentals, keeping my margin of safety, investing with a medium/long term
horizon and being patient, making sure that mgt is honest and invested, many
times taking contrarian approaches and personally downloading SEC data and
putting my spreadsheet together".

I emailed you something. check it out.
